# CYOA EXPORT (full story)
# story: Tutorial
# date: 2026-06-13T14:02:53.897Z
# ---
NODE|1A|Fox|L|Introduction||Hello!\n\nWelcome to The Den. If you've read the first screen, you're already familiar with that this tool does, but essentially, it is a very simple and accessible tool for creating branching narratives while focusing heavily on the writing portion of traditional CYOAs. This tool is for everyone who enjoys the classic CYOA structure but likes focusing on prose, worldbuilding, and long-form writing.\n\nThe point is writing, sharing, and reading. It's also a massive love letter to the old internet when things where simple, lightweight, and didn't spike your RAM just to inject hundreds of trackers into your every click.\n\nIt is a single-file, fully self-contained engine that handles... A lot. As you'll learn. Don't let the simple look fool you.\n\nI'm the creator of this tool, as you can see in the lower left corner. That is where your signature will be once you decide to write your own story.\n\nYou can go into settings and disable author names if you prefer a cleaner view.\n\nThis interactive story will teach you all of the basics in a (hopefully) digestible way so you aren't stuck reading a massive help screen, but if you do want the comprehensive list, which is always available as a refresher, it's at the bottom of the hamburger menu and contains **ALL** of the information you could possibly need.\n\nFor the best "experience" I expect you to actually read everything and not skip around. Each node will tell you where to go since I don't want you getting lost. Prioritize the order I specified, usually shorter branches will go first. If you miss a node, then you might not know how a basic feature works.\n\nMost importantly, this site never collects your data. Everything you write is stored in your device's storage using Dexie. It never leaves your phone/computer/smart toaster, and can hold much more data than LocalStorage. If you're on the website version of this tool, all the server does is send an HTML file to your device, and this .cyoa tutorial story file bundled in. Nothing is ever sent back, everything remains private, and the whole thing is smaller in size than an average blurry smartphone photo.\n\nThere are also no ads because I despise them, they would ruin the point of this project, and there is no way for you to give me money (sorry, not sorry). If you do want to support this anyway, read about it at the bottom of the side menu by clicking the support and contact button. I threw in the most basic option, but honestly, as long as you're here and participate by writing and having fun, that's already a lot more than I could've hoped for.\n\n**Small disclaimer:** This app was, and still partially is something I made for personal use. You might encounter a bug or two, but I am actively working on it.\n\nTo start your tutorial, look below. You will see a text preview. On the right of it is a downward-facing arrow, press it to preview the text, then click it to select and open it in the full viewer, or just click it directly. If you don't see a text preview, you might have flipped the spoiler mode on which will only show a subtitle. If the arrow is there, you're good.
NODE|1B|Fox||Basic tree explanation||This is node 1B, and it's a good time to explain how this tree works. If you need more reading space, click the downward-facing arrow next to the "Choices" label to collapse them.\n\nAn easy way to visualize branching timelines is with the main identifier (1) and spot you are currently on within that timeline (B). The letter B is the second letter in the alphabet, so this is Timeline 1 - Spot 2. This goes on sequentially, and each timeline is completely isolated. If you ever get lost, the Tree View option can show you the whole thing visually. If you ever need to grab the current address you're on for copy-pasting, click the address name up there in the banner next to the ominous green circle.\n\nIt's actually pretty cool, you can easily see at a glance where in the story you are by address alone. After you write node 1Z, the next one will roll over to 1AA, then 1AB, 1AC, and so on. If you've ever used Excel, this is pretty standard for you.\n\nBy navigating with the bar below, you can go back to 1A easily. Pressing the back button on a root node will show you other root nodes that are separate from 1A, e.g. 2A, 3A, and so on.\n\nRemember: All timelines are accessible within the same story, and each story is an isolated file. 1A (timeline 1, first node) and 2A (timeline 2, first node) are physically separated, but you can go from one to another with zero issues by using the search tool, the tree view or navigating back from the root node.\n\n**_BEFORE YOU CONTINUE_**—and I cannot stress this enough—go into the side menu and flip the Spoiler mode setting. It should say **"Spoilers: Hidden."** I've made sure the subtitles serve as a guide on where you should go next. You should only see a small subtitle instead of text previews for the rest of this tutorial. Do you see "Branching explanation (shorter)" below this text? Yes? Good, now you can actually proceed. If you don't do this, you'll get lost. Follow along, shorter branches first, then longer ones.
NODE|1B1A|Fox|L|Continuation (longer)||Since you've read 1C, now you understand basic branching. Here's a question:\n\nIf you branched from here, what would the branch name be called? \n\n1B1A2?\n1B1AB?\n1B1A1A?\n\nThat's right, 1B1A1A. You take the node you are on now (1B1A) and slap another 1A onto it. It's all done automatically so you don't have to actually worry about this stuff, but if you want to preserve your sanity, use the handy-dandy bookmark feature.\n\nYou can branch multiple times after each node. If you branched from 1B1A while 1B1A1A exists, it would default to 1B1A2A. It all follows a simple (debatable) and logical (non-debatable) flow. \n\nThere is one thing you should keep in mind. There is no timeline merging, or infinite loops. They can only split. \n\nIt's not that it's not possible, I just haven't figured out how to make it fun yet. The idea is that if you wish to branch, you actually need to... Well, commit to that branch. Otherwise you'd have to consider a million little choices that converged into one line.  Until I know how to make it a fun gameplay/reading mechanic, you should treat each branch as a deliberate choice.\n\nHowever, this doesn't necessarily mean you have to rewrite your story just because your character had an option to either eat an apple or a greasy burger for breakfast. Explained later, don't worry about it.\n\nOnce you start writing, have a good reason to branch. It's useful for writing different endings, side stories, sub-plots, worldbuilding, and so on, but not for tiny decisions that have to converge without affecting the story in any way (also known as Illusion of Choice that this format is prone to. Think Telltale games for example.)\n\nHowever, it does amazingly well with the trope where you want to drop the plot for a while to track some random idiot in a completely different genre or AU. Mordor slice-of-life? Go for it. Dark era of a wholesome plot? Even better. Glup Shitto as the main character gets their own isolated plot and you can kill them off whenever.\n\nFor this, you'll have to know how ratings work, and how you can gate people from reading your edgy writing. Explained in 1B1A1A.
NODE|1B1A1A|Fox|L|Rest of the features (longer section)||Let's start with ratings, choices, subtitles and the rest, so open this node in the editor. Since this is your first time checking it out, it might feel cramped, but there is a button to give you more space to work.\n\nAt the bottom, you can see two options, one for the Subtitles and three letters, L, M and H. Let's handle Subtitles.\n\nThe subtitles are what you show your reader if they have the Spoiler Mode toggled, it will only show what you want them to see instead of the text preview. You can use this to mark big decisions such as "Save [character]" or "Ignore [character]" without letting your readers metagame the outcomes.\n\nThe next node will show you how ratings work with a choice between three, each containing a different explanation, it's the best way to show you how ratings and choices are handled.
NODE|1B1A1B|Fox||Content ratings||This spot branches into three different paths. Each has a different rating, but don't worry, all of the content is safe to read. If you see only one, you've probably selected the green option at the start of the tutorial story, so go into options and change "Max content rating" to H. \n\nDepending on your reader's setting, they will **only** see the selected level, and all the levels below it. L shows only L, M shows M and L, H shows all available options.\n\nThe content rating of the node you're on is displayed with a colored indicator above it. \n\nIf you change the content rating of the node at the root of that specific branch, keep in mind that _ALL_ of the nodes after it will inherit that rating, regardless if they belong to the main path or a side story. This is by design, because if you wrote smut in one branch, lowering a side branch to L would be pointless since the reader would have to go through the adult content to get to it anyway. You can still do it, though, because I'm not a fed and can't tell you what to do. <3\n\nNow, pick one of the three nodes to learn about a specific feature. Remember to change the setting if you don't see exactly three options. \n\nThe main tutorial will continue on the green line so do this order:\n\n1. Read the H line first.\n2. Read the M line next.\n3. Continue on the L line.
NODE|1B1A1B1A|Fox|M|M (and shuffle explanation)||The Shuffle option you see in the nav bar is how this tool handles "metagaming" or "picking the obviously correct choice." \n\nWhen someone reads your story and you wrote several options for them to choose from, the tool randomizes them each time the options are loaded. They can pick from the three randomly chosen ones, or see all the available options in the side menu. \n\nI've written four new nodes for you to see this in practice. They were added in order (1,2,3,4) but you should see only three, sorted randomly.\n\nYou can also collapse the choices bar if it gets in the way, for easier reading.\n\nSpam the shuffle button a bit, play around, edit yours if you want, then go back to the L node to continue learning.
NODE|1B1A1B1A1A|Fox|M|2||2
NODE|1B1A1B1A2A|Fox|M|3||3
NODE|1B1A1B1A3A|Fox|M|4||4
NODE|1B1A1B1B|Fox||1||1
NODE|1B1A1B2A|Fox|H|H (and formatting tricks)||This is the H-rated node. Here, you would start writing your super-gritty, hyper-violent, or just smutty fiction. As you can see in the editor, you can edit this node's rating freely, and it will crawl up the rest of the branch, updating the rating of every node.\n\nHowever, this one sadly has no such edgy/smutty content so while you're here, check out the writing tools in the editor. You can add **bold**, *italics*, and _underline_, by pressing the button, or just do it manually as you write. You can also combine them _***like this***_ by pressing all the buttons you'd like active at the same time.\n\nAdditionally, I have added {red:colors!} Works the same in the editor, press the color picker, put the text in the curly braces, done. {#00d9d9:Custom hex codes work too!}\n\nJust be careful with links. Or... Just combining multiple options at once. It will likely work, but the order can take some getting used to. I did make sure colors and links work together, if the links mode is off, the text will appear colored, if they are on, links take priority. You can also format the display text inside the link, but not the key portion, so [[**link**|key]] should work if link display is on, and {red:[[link|key]]} should also work if links display is off. If you ever decide to combine like 5 variants, good luck!\n\nThe ((**jump**|1B1A1B2A)) button should work with most formatting styles.\n\nIf you want to make the text bigger, use ##hashtags##. Or whatever they were called in the old days. Minimum of two, paired on each side of the text you want to resize, maxes at four. \n\n##Size +1##\n###Size +2###\n####Size +3####\n\nThis order of syntax gets confusing even for me so just experiment or read the help screen when formatting ends up not working. If something should work because I said it would, and yet it doesn't, then it's my fault, hit me up and I'll fix it instead of pleading the fifth. \n\nContinue from here to learn about the biggest addition I've added in months.\n\nAnyway, how do you feel about\n\n##{{dendefault:{orange:glyphs}}}?## \n\nOr perhaps █████████?\n\nPick one, read both. Redaction is shorter so do that first.
NODE|1B1A1B2A1A|Fox|H|REDACTION!||Redaction is the only destructive formatting option here and it's very simple to do, but you need to trust the program, not your device.\n\nWhen you select text, Android or maybe even Windows will collapse the selection. Here, it doesn't matter. Open the editor.\n\nRedact this text.\n\nPress and hold on that text above or select it with your mouse, press +, then "Redact selection". Simple, easy, mysterious, spooky even.\n\nRemember that there is no undo for this so be careful.\n\nNow go back and read about those ominous glyphs you've seen (arguably the more fun part).
NODE|1B1A1B2B|Fox||GLYPHS!||That's right, you can insert actual inline eldritch tongues straight into your writing now. \n\nI'm super hyped about it because it took me a long time to figure it out but it finally works! So buckle your fuckles and let me show you how it works.\n\nFirst, usage. You use a custom font by wrapping your text in syntax. In this case two curly braces {{ followed by your font name, "dendefault" for example, a colon ":", space, then the text you want to glyph-ify, then another two curly braces. Works with a space between curly braces too. So you get {{dendefault: this}}. You can even color them like {{dendefault: {orange: this}}} or resize and color such as ###{{dendefault: {#ff0000: that}}}###.\n\nMaking your own is extremely simple, press the + button in the editor toolbar and then Manage custom fonts. Name it, pick the grid size you wish your glyphs to render at, and pick a style.\n\nStyles are basically ways to give your alien languages identity. Squared will retain sharp angles, rounded will still be angled just with softened corners, and flowing will use a more fluid style. \n\nOnce you've created the first glyph for a set, the size gets locked in for that set. You can always change the style of it if you don't like the flow, and you can change the thickness per-glyph. \n\nYou can easily insert them by pressing + then "Insert glyph text" which will immediately insert the syntax you can paste your text in.\n\nI've also built a tool that can randomize glyphs for you to have a starting point instead of drawing each one from scratch. This is just math and SVGs, it just randomly creates lines based on a complexity scale. You saw the glyphs earlier, they followed the sharp style at high complexity, with my own manual editing after they were randomized. You can easily mix and match them, you aren't locked into a specific complexity or thickness. For example this is the letter a: {{dendefault: a}}.\n\nPersonally, I think sharp, thick ones look best right out of the box, and if you use the flowing ones they will likely require your own touch since organic shapes are inherently more chaotic. Give it a shot, the possibilities are literally endless. Well, as long as they fit in a 16x16 or smaller grid kind of endless. You get the point.\n\nBut that's it for glyphs. It was a lot of work and a pain to add, and only now I realized that it's actually super easy to explain. Maybe I'm just trusting you, the reader, to poke around and figure it out for yourself. It's super easy, I promise. :D\n\nJust remember that it's case sensitive and you need to assign one to each letter, number, and punctuation in the menu. They will still work if you just assign the ones you need, you don't have to fill the full set if you just need to write WARNING.\n\nAlso, they are exported and imported with your tree or branch. That's why naming is important, they will get overwritten if you import a font with the same name. Keep them unique just in case you don't overwrite someone else's or your own fonts.\n\nNow go back to the M-rated node and continue with the tutorial.
NODE|1B1A1C|Fox||L (and the continuation of the tutorial)||This line continues the tutorial so here is a smaller thing to keep in mind.\n\nDeleting nodes doesn't actually delete the addresses themselves. If you open the tree view, you can easily see that there are a few empty nodes I used in testing. They are completely harmless. If you delete a node and write a continuation or a branch, the program will just fill the first available node. \n\nYou can click the eye icon in the tree view to hide empty nodes if they're an eyesore. The viewer isn't static and refreshes on each visit anyway.\n\nClicking "Write Next" writes the continuation of the node you are on by incrementing the last letter.\n\nClicking "Branch" adds a "1A" suffix and continues from there. \n\nIf you empty a node, for example 1B while you have 1A and 1C, the choice for 1C will appear in the picker while you're at 1A so the reader won't actually see the empty node, unless they click and hold the forward button.\n\nKeep in mind that to branch from a node, you need to have the main continuation active. Narratively these "main" and "side" branches are irrelevant, you can continue your story on a side branch and keep it going forever, but the system needs that "main" node to exist by clicking "write next" first. Otherwise the forward button logic breaks. \n\nAgain, in practice this doesn't really matter, you can write the story anywhere you please. However, try to minimize gaps and deletions if you'd like to keep your tree view tidy. They get greyed out, but they will always be visible.\n\nWhen navigating with Back and Forward buttons, a short press will skip emptied nodes. A long press (or click) will not.
NODE|1B1A1D|Fox||Glossary||Glossary is arguably the coolest feature of this site and I'm super proud of it. \n\nIn usual CYOAs you can't really have a wiki for your characters or events because creating an article would spoil everything that ever happens related to them. The solution was to treat entries as separate pages, keeping them aware of the place they are on within the timeline, and making sure they respond to the same key or tag. If that sounds like a lot of nonsense... Yeah, I don't have an out for you here, you still need to finish the tutorial.\n\nFirst, you need to know how to make and edit a glossary entry, so go to the side menu and click "Links: hidden" to toggle them.\n\nThen, open this node in the editor to learn how to make one.\n\nAre you in the editor? Cool. You place two pieces of text in double square brackets like this:\n\n[[John Adventure|john_adventure]]\n\nThe system follows the logic of using Actual Name, followed by a pipe (|) then the entry it will occupy the wikipedia, a key if you will. The first portion will show up in the viewport and be clickable.\n\nOnce that is hooked up in the text editor, you need to save the node, and click the link in the viewport. It will ask you if you'd like to create an entry for that character you clicked, but I've already done that for the first one, so just click it and read about John.\n\nOnce you've read the entry for Mr. Adventure, try creating your own here:\n\n[[example|key]]\n\nChange it to anything you like (name|key), click it after saving the node, and fill some information in, this is not optional, you **_will_** do it. :)\n\nKeep in mind that multiple things can lead to the same wiki entry. You can write anything before the pipe, as long as the key after it leads where you'd like it to. So for example [[Adventure Man|john_adventure]] can lead to the same entry as John Adventure.\n\nAfter that's done, head to the next node to see how this system prevents spoilers.
NODE|1B1A1D1A|Fox|L||E|
NODE|1B1A1D2A|Fox|L||E|
NODE|1B1A1D3A|Fox|L||E|
NODE|1B1A1D4A|Fox|L||E|
NODE|1B1A1E|Fox||Glossary continued||Here you can see how we can prevent spoilers. I'm going to create the same wiki entry as I did in the last node:\n\n[[John Adventure|john_adventure]]\n\nOnce I click it, it will ask me if I would like to empty it or copy the contents from the previous entry. I copy them, then I fill it up with updated information by appending a paragraph.\n\nIf you click it now, it will have two paragraphs total. Going back to the previous node, you can see that the same wiki entry for John remained completely unchanged, but here it shows additional info. \n\nWiki entries can do this once per node per wiki entry. It works by stamping where the entry was created, thus limiting what shows up earlier in the timeline. If you have multiple branches, and multiple occurences of the same key, it will use the earliest one it can find by crawling backward, timelines stay isolated.\n\nYou can use this to keep notes of various characters without polluting old versions, or just worldbuild in a timeline-aware fashion. Old info remains where it should be, new info keeps evolving every time you add an update. Your readers will be able to refresh their memory without seeing a giant "**_STATUS: DECEASED_**" banner when opening a character's page for the first time. \n\nYou can edit your own from the last step here, make sure that the key matches the previous one. The wiki is only sensitive to keys, that's the secret sauce that keeps spoilers away. The names of those keys are completely irrelevant which is why multiple things can lead to the same entry.\n\n[[example|key]]\n\nAgain, none of this is stored anywhere other than your device and the .cyoa export you can create. There is no database, and the server doesn't receive any information from you, everything is a one-way street.\n\nContinue onward to learn about the chaos mechanic.
NODE|1B1A1E1A|Fox|L||E|
NODE|1B1A1F|Fox||Forced shift||The option "Forced shift" in the side menu is a tool made to keep you on your toes, go back and forth randomly, and maybe flesh out side stories or create new branches. \n\nEvery time you navigate by picking a choice, pressing a button on the nav bar, or selecting a node in the tree view, the counter goes up following the 0/1, 1/1, 0/2, 1/2... pattern. Each time it hits the goal, you are thrown randomly somewhere in the tree.\n\nWhy would anyone need this? Because you write ideas and they sit in drafts without ever being touched again, that's why. You know who you are. \n\nPlus, if you're reading a community tree with thousands of nodes, it might be fun to try and piece together the stories as an amnesiac time traveler. It's completely optional so don't worry about it if it's not your thing.\n\nAlthough this one will work best once people actually start writing stories you can import... So if there are none, congrats, you're one of the first people here. :D Do you like the font by the way? Readable? I picked it because it seemed less "robotic" and one Tumblr post said the weirder your font, the more you're motivated to write. \n\nAt least it's not Comic Sans.\n\nI'm adding more tutorial here, so read about pictures next!
NODE|1B1A1F1A|Fox|L|Pictures!||I've added an option to import images into your nodes. If you press the + button you can insert it anywhere and it will show up on its own line as a file name, but will display fully once you save the node.\n\nThese also survive exports and imports, so if you want to draw your research logs or odd places, that would make your worldbuilding even better.
NODE|1B1A1G|Fox||(Last)||And... That's it. You conquered the hardest boss of the day, the one thing that we all struggle with... Reading. Especially mad rambling of a fox running on several cups of coffee and a dream.\n\nI'm joking, I do appreciate that you actually stuck around. Making this was so incredibly fun (and sometimes incredibly frustrating), but I hope that you or someone else will see the vision and decide to explore your creativity, either on your own, or by joining the community. It's intended for collaboration but is also a completely self-contained program you can use on your own. \n\nThanks for being here, and make sure to download the code for this site if you want a true offline experience.\n\nIf you've never run an HTML file, you will have some trouble with Chrome on Android since it conveniently "forgets" the file it just opened (probably to keep you in their ecosystem), so keep it on your home screen or something. As long as you don't erase history, everything will stay as is. If you've never used an HTML file raw before... Hang tight, eventually I'll figure out how to make an app or take another crack at PWAs (Progressive Web Apps). Last time it was a total nightmare because of Google themselves. Is that oversharing? I mean you've read this far, you're accustomed to rambling.\n\nBye!
NODE|1B1B|Fox||Grafting (shorter section).||To understand grafting, you need to understand exporting first.\n\nIn the side menu there is a button you can press.\n\nIf you export a branch from here, you would export 1B1B and theoretically all of the nodes that come _after_ it. So 1B1C, 1B1D, 1B1E and so on. Think of it like literally cutting off a branch and gluing it to another tree.\n\nIf you export the whole story, that would scoop up all of the timelines as a single file that someone can import anywhere.\n\nExporting a **PATH** however, is the option you take when you want someone to read a completely linear story up to that point. It would take the exact linear path from your current node backward until it reaches 1A, the starting point. So in this case exporting a path would take \n\n1B1B\n1B1A\n1B\n1A\n\nand then put them in a .txt file. Pretty cool, right? You could be down several thousand nodes and you'd still have a fully contained story since it would ignore all of the side branches.\n\nContinue from here to learn about importing and how this tool makes it easy for you to plop a story anywhere you like, regardless where it sat on the tree you got it from.
NODE|1B1C|Fox||Importing and exporting in-depth.||Importing works by taking a .cyoa file and picking a node where you would like to put it.\n\nThe catch is that, since this structure is completely unique, only files made by this tool (website or the theoretical app down the line) will work. You cannot import a raw text file, it needs to be made with this, and end in .cyoa. The CYOA files contain data about addresses, ratings, authors and many other things which simply had to be contained in their own extension.\n\nThis is how:\n\n1. You grab a .cyoa file from a friend or from the community. \n2. You go to any node, like this one.\n3. You press "Import" while you're already at that node.\n4. The tool simply creates a new branch or continuation at that node, and everything becomes available as usual.\n\nYou might be wondering about addresses? If you import someone's story branch that starts with 1F, but want to slot it in at your own 1C, won't that ruin the whole thing?\n\nNope, they will just get systematically rewritten. If you import a branch 1F -> 1G -> 1H -> 1I -> 1J and so on, your version would depend on whether or not you have a node called 1D. If not, their branch becomes 1D -> 1E -> 1F -> 1G -> 1H. If you do already have a node 1D, then it would be rewritten by branching from 1C, so 1C1A -> 1C1B -> 1C1C -> 1C1D -> 1C1E. \n\nKeep in mind that this specific feature has been the cause of the most all-nighters, so keep things backed up in case it decides to not do its intended job. Contact me if it ever goes wrong and I'll fix the bug, I would hate for you to lose hours of work like I did in the early phases of making this. There is a lot of moving parts so it's inevitable that someone might eventually find a way to completely nuke their entire tree, and that keeps me up at night.\n\nAnyway, since you just finished the exporting/importing branch, read about creating makeshift loops next, then go back to 1B1A to continue exploring the rest of the features and learn more.
NODE|1B1D|Fox||Looping (very evil)||If you do want to create a loop, you cannot just connect the node 1C to 1A (yet). But nothing is stopping you from exporting 1A, 1B, 1C, and attaching it onto 1C again, which would then turn 1A into 1D, 1B into 1E and 1C into 1F. In theory, you could just go to an end-point of a sprawling story and just sneakily glue the entire tree starting from 1A. \n\nAlthough, don't do that, that would be evil. And... Would waste their time. Totally don't do that. :3\n\nThere is also the jump button which you can use to send the reader anywhere without restrictions, probably a simpler option than exporting and importing the whole tree.\n\nSince we'll go back to the rest of the tutorial at 1B1A1A, we want to create a clickable link. You can use the button on the right in the editor that looks like an upward arrow. It will insert ((|)) for you. The display text goes before the pipe, and the address you wish to jump to goes after the pipe. Like so. These will be animated with a subtle glow so they stand out from wiki links.\n\n((Click here!|1B1A1A))\n\nBy clicking that, you're immediately thrown to the next node in the tutorial, you won't miss anything.
NODE|1C|Fox||Branching explanation (shorter)||The way branching works is by taking the node you just came from, and appending 1A to it. \n\nCurrently you are on 1C, however if you go back one step, you will notice 1B1A. As you can see, it is a branch of (1B), the first branch (1) first spot (A).\n\nBasically, the numbers indicate timelines (1, 2, 3) and letters indicate places on that timeline (A, B, C). \n\nIf you branch from a branch, that also works, the only cost is the length of the address. Go to the previous node and select 1B1A, then follow it along.
